                <head>343. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 1, 1962, President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> chaired
                    a White House meeting on the Dominican situation according to the President’s
                    Appointment Book. (Kennedy Library) Present were Under Secretary of State
                        <persName corresp="#p_MGGC2">McGhee</persName>, Assistant Secretary of State
                    for Inter-American Affairs <persName corresp="#p_MEW2">Edwin Martin</persName>,
                    Ambassador to the Dominican Republic <persName corresp="#p_MJB2">John Bartlow
                        Martin</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PR9">Rafael Pico</persName>,
                    temporary U.S. coordinator of economic aid to the Dominican Republic, Teodoro
                    Moscoso and Newell Williams of <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss>, [<hi
                        rend="italic">text not declassified</hi>] of <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                        >CIA</gloss>, and <persName corresp="#p_DRA1">Ralph Dungan</persName> of the
                    White House staff. No formal record of the meeting was kept. During the meeting,
                    which lasted from 4:30 to 5:27 p.m., the President inquired about the Dominican
                    sugar quota, the upcoming Dominican elections, the activities of the recently
                    established <gloss target="#t_MAAG1">MAAG</gloss> in Santo Domingo, and the
                    chances of a military coup in the Dominican Republic. He asked that the
                    Dominican police force receive U.S. instruction in riot control techniques.
                        (<persName>Martin</persName>, Overtaken by Events, pages 121-122)</p>
